<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910220-0069</DOCNO><DOCID>910220-0069.</DOCID><HL>   Who's News:   Bells' Research Arm   Chooses Heilmeier   For Two Top Posts</HL><DATE>02/20/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B8</SO><CO>   BEL WNEWS BLS USW SBC AIT PAC NYN</CO><IN>TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)</IN><LP>   LIVINGSTON, N.J. -- Bell Communications Research Inc.chose George H. Heilmeier, senior vice president and chieftechnical officer of Texas Instruments Inc., as president andchief executive officer beginning March 1.   He succeeds Rocco J. Marano, 63 years old, who isretiring. Mr. Marano, Bellcore's president and chiefexecutive since the company was formed in the 1984 breakup ofthe Bell System, was named chairman until his May 1retirement. Bellcore is the shared research and engineeringarm of the seven regional Bell telephone companies. It alsocoordinates national security matters for the Bells.</LP><TEXT>   Mr. Heilmeier, 54, has held top positions in TexasInstruments' research and technology programs since 1977. In1983, he was named to his current post with responsibilitiesfor all research and development, engineering, corporatedevelopment and strategic planning.   Before that, Mr. Heilmeier, a native of Philadelphia, waswith RCA Laboratories, where his work with electro-opticeffects in liquid crystals led to liquid crystal displays forwatches, calculators and various instruments. He was selectedas a White House Fellow in 1970 and a year later was named tohead the Department of Defense's research in electronics andphysical sciences. He became director of the Defense AdvancedResearch Projects Agency in 1975.   Mr. Heilmeier said he was attracted to Bellcore because ofthe diversity of activities there and a belief that Bellcorewill continue to play an important role in the informationrevolution.</TEXT></DOC>